, with the vertex longer. The conical protuberance and tuft of hair on the supraclypeal area in the male is not found in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1923" box="[1247,1401,1221,1246]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Xerophasma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1247,1401,1221,1246]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Xerophasma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or elsewhere in the genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,586,1546]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,285,1296,1322]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Range.</emphasis>
Apparently endemic to Death Valley (
<figureCitation box="[758,849,1296,1322]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23" captionStartId="8.[151,269,517,541]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,495]" captionTargetId="figure-485@8.[151,1436,194,495]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. Habitus of female Perdita (Xerophasma). Perdita celadona (21), P. vespertina (22), P. rhondae (23)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302220" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302220/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). Known only from dunes near Stovepipe Wells where it was active at dusk.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[198,1020,1370,1396]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,586,1546]" box="[198,1020,1370,1396]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,323,1370,1396]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Variation.</emphasis>
The size of the dark markings varies slightly in both sexes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,586,1546]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,1408,1434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species was discovered after we thought we had completed this manuscript. It is a great pleasure to name this bee after my wife Rhonda, who has been my companion on many an entomological quest, and who discovered these bees on 
<taxonomicName box="[645,785,1483,1508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Camissonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[645,785,1483,1508]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Camissonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as we were leaving the dunes near Stovepipe Wells at dusk.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
